- Object payloads have `cwd` added via spread; primitive payloads are wrapped in `{ content, cwd }`
- All existing BindingRouter tests pass after updating assertions for the enriched payload
- New tests verify CWD enrichment for both object and primitive payloads

Fix Bug 3: `streamKey(channelId, threadTs?)` returns just `channelId` when `threadTs` is undefined. Two concurrent responses in the same channel share a key, causing the second to edit the first's message. This is a three-part fix.

## Part 3a: Harden resolveThreadTs

**File:** `packages/relay/src/adapters/slack/outbound.ts`

The current `resolveThreadTs` at line 83-97 already checks `pd.threadTs` and `pd.ts`, but the string checks don't guard against empty strings. Add emptiness guards:

```typescript
function resolveThreadTs(envelope: RelayEnvelope): string | undefined {
  const payload = envelope.payload;
  if (payload === null || typeof payload !== 'object') return undefined;

  const obj = payload as Record<string, unknown>;
  const pd = obj.platformData as Record<string, unknown> | undefined;
  if (!pd) return undefined;

  // threadTs takes precedence (already in a thread)
  if (typeof pd.threadTs === 'string' && pd.threadTs) return pd.threadTs;
  // ts of the original message (always present for inbound Slack messages)
  if (typeof pd.ts === 'string' && pd.ts) return pd.ts;

  return undefined;
}
```

The change is adding `&& pd.threadTs` and `&& pd.ts` emptiness guards to the two string checks.

## Part 3b: Synthetic fallback for programmatic messages

In `deliverMessage`, after the existing `const threadTs = resolveThreadTs(envelope);` (line ~369), add a synthetic fallback using the envelope ID:

```typescript
const threadTs = resolveThreadTs(envelope);
// Synthetic fallback: use envelope ID to prevent collisions for programmatic messages
const effectiveThreadTs = threadTs ?? envelope.id;
```

Then replace all uses of `threadTs` in the StreamEvent handlers with `effectiveThreadTs`:

- In the `text_delta` handler call: `handleTextDelta(channelId, textChunk, effectiveThreadTs, client, streamState, callbacks, startTime)`
- In the `error` handler call: `handleError(channelId, errorMsg, effectiveThreadTs, client, streamState, callbacks, startTime)`
- In the `done` handler call: `handleDone(channelId, effectiveThreadTs, client, streamState, callbacks, startTime)`

For the standard payload (non-StreamEvent) path, continue using `threadTs` (not the fallback) so that non-stream messages without thread context are sent to the channel root.

## Part 3c: Add streamId to ActiveStream for race detection

Update the `ActiveStream` interface to include a unique stream identifier:

```typescript
export interface ActiveStream {
  /** Unique identifier for this stream, used for race detection logging. */
  streamId: string;
  /** The channel ID being streamed to. */
  channelId: string;
  /** The thread_ts to reply under. */
  threadTs: string;
  /** The message ts returned by chat.postMessage (updated by streaming). */
  messageTs: string;
  /** Accumulated raw Markdown text content for the stream. */
  accumulatedText: string;
  /** Timestamp (ms) of the last chat.update call -- used for throttling. */
  lastUpdateAt: number;
  /** Timestamp (ms) when the stream was created -- used for TTL reaping. */
  startedAt: number;
}
```

In `handleTextDelta`, when starting a new stream, add `streamId`:

```typescript
streamState.set(key, {
  streamId: crypto.randomUUID(),
  channelId,
  threadTs: threadTs ?? '',
  messageTs: (result as { ts?: string }).ts ?? '',
  accumulatedText: textChunk,
  lastUpdateAt: now,
  startedAt: now,
});
```

Add the `crypto` import at the top of the file:
```typescript
import { randomUUID } from 'node:crypto';
```

Use `randomUUID()` instead of `crypto.randomUUID()` for Node.js compatibility.

## Tests

**File:** `packages/relay/src/adapters/slack/__tests__/outbound.test.ts`

Add a new `describe('streaming -- stream key isolation')` block. Update the `createEnvelope` helper to accept an optional `id` parameter, or create envelopes with unique IDs:

```typescript
describe('streaming -- stream key isolation', () => {
  it('uses platformData.ts as thread anchor when threadTs is undefined', async () => {
    const envelope = createEnvelope('relay.human.slack.D123', {
      type: 'text_delta',
      data: { text: 'Hello' },
      platformData: { ts: '1234.0001' },
    });
    await deliver('relay.human.slack.D123', envelope, client, streamState, callbacks);

    // Stream key should include ts value: 'D123:1234.0001'
    expect(streamState.has('D123:1234.0001')).toBe(true);
    expect(streamState.has('D123')).toBe(false);
  });

  it('uses envelope.id as fallback when no platformData exists', async () => {
    const envelope = createEnvelope('relay.human.slack.D123', {
      type: 'text_delta',
      data: { text: 'Hello' },
    });
    await deliver('relay.human.slack.D123', envelope, client, streamState, callbacks);

    // Stream key should use envelope.id fallback: 'D123:env-01'
    expect(streamState.has('D123:env-01')).toBe(true);
    expect(streamState.has('D123')).toBe(false);
  });

  it('concurrent responses in same channel use separate stream state', async () => {
    const envelope1 = {
      ...createEnvelope('relay.human.slack.D123', {
        type: 'text_delta',
        data: { text: 'Response 1' },
        platformData: { ts: '1111.0001' },
      }),
      id: 'env-a',
    };
    const envelope2 = {
      ...createEnvelope('relay.human.slack.D123', {
        type: 'text_delta',
        data: { text: 'Response 2' },
        platformData: { ts: '2222.0002' },
      }),
      id: 'env-b',
    };

    await deliver('relay.human.slack.D123', envelope1, client, streamState, callbacks);
    await deliver('relay.human.slack.D123', envelope2, client, streamState, callbacks);

    // Two separate stream entries
    expect(streamState.size).toBe(2);
    expect(streamState.has('D123:1111.0001')).toBe(true);
    expect(streamState.has('D123:2222.0002')).toBe(true);
    // Two separate chat.postMessage calls
    expect(mockPostMessage).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(2);
  });

  it('guards against empty string threadTs in platformData', async () => {
    const envelope = createEnvelope('relay.human.slack.D123', {
      type: 'text_delta',
      data: { text: 'Hello' },
      platformData: { ts: '' },
    });
    await deliver('relay.human.slack.D123', envelope, client, streamState, callbacks);

    // Empty ts should fall through to envelope.id fallback
    expect(streamState.has('D123:env-01')).toBe(true);
  });
});
```

Update existing tests that check `streamState.has('D123')` -- they will now need to account for the envelope.id-based key (`D123:env-01`). The `createEnvelope` helper uses `id: 'env-01'` by default, so the key will be `D123:env-01` when no `platformData.ts` is present.

## Acceptance Criteria

- `resolveThreadTs` returns undefined for empty-string threadTs/ts values
- Programmatic messages without platformData use `envelope.id` as a synthetic thread key
- Two concurrent responses in the same channel never share a stream key
- `ActiveStream` includes a `streamId` field populated with `randomUUID()`
- All existing streaming tests pass after updating stream key assertions

Fix Bug 1: `slackify-markdown` (v5.0.0) inserts `\n\n` paragraph separators during intermediate updates, causing each streaming chunk to appear on a new line instead of flowing continuously. The fix collapses consecutive newlines for intermediate `chat.update` calls only, while preserving full paragraph formatting in the final `handleDone` update.

## Implementation

**File:** `packages/relay/src/adapters/slack/outbound.ts`

In `handleTextDelta`, modify the existing `chat.update` call (line ~172-180) to collapse paragraph breaks for intermediate streaming updates:

```typescript
if (existing) {
  // Accumulate raw Markdown -- converted to mrkdwn at send time
  existing.accumulatedText += textChunk;

  // Throttle: skip chat.update if called less than STREAM_UPDATE_INTERVAL_MS ago.
  const now = Date.now();
  if (now - existing.lastUpdateAt < STREAM_UPDATE_INTERVAL_MS) {
    return { success: true, durationMs: now - startTime };
  }
  existing.lastUpdateAt = now;

  const formatted = formatForPlatform(existing.accumulatedText, 'slack');
  // Collapse paragraph breaks for intermediate streaming updates only.
  // The final handleDone update preserves full paragraph formatting.
  const streamText = formatted.replace(/\n{2,}/g, '\n');

  return wrapSlackCall(
    () => client.chat.update({
      channel: channelId,
      ts: existing.messageTs,
      text: truncateText(streamText, MAX_MESSAGE_LENGTH),
    }),
    callbacks,
    startTime,
  );
}
```

The `handleDone` function already calls `formatForPlatform()` without any newline collapsing, so the final message retains proper paragraph structure. No changes needed there.

## Tests

**File:** `packages/relay/src/adapters/slack/__tests__/outbound.test.ts`

Add a new `describe('streaming -- intermediate newline collapsing')` block:

```typescript
describe('streaming -- intermediate newline collapsing', () => {
  it('collapses consecutive newlines in intermediate chat.update calls', async () => {
    // Start a stream
    const delta1 = createEnvelope('relay.human.slack.D123', {
      type: 'text_delta',
      data: { text: 'Line 1' },
    });
    await deliver('relay.human.slack.D123', delta1, client, streamState, callbacks);

    // Advance past throttle window
    nowMs += 1_001;

    // The mock formatForPlatform is a passthrough, so we simulate what
    // slackify-markdown does by having accumulated text with paragraph breaks
    // We directly set accumulated text with paragraph breaks to test the collapse
    const key = Array.from(streamState.keys())[0]!;
    streamState.get(key)!.accumulatedText = 'Line 1\n\nLine 2\n\n\nLine 3';

    const delta2 = createEnvelope('relay.human.slack.D123', {
      type: 'text_delta',
      data: { text: '' },
    });
    await deliver('relay.human.slack.D123', delta2, client, streamState, callbacks);

    // Intermediate update should have collapsed newlines
    const updateCall = mockChatUpdate.mock.calls[0]?.[0] as { text: string };
    expect(updateCall.text).toBe('Line 1\nLine 2\nLine 3');
    expect(updateCall.text).not.toContain('\n\n');
  });

  it('preserves paragraph formatting in final handleDone update', async () => {
    // Start a stream
    const delta = createEnvelope('relay.human.slack.D123', {
      type: 'text_delta',
      data: { text: 'Para 1\n\nPara 2' },
    });
    await deliver('relay.human.slack.D123', delta, client, streamState, callbacks);

    // Send done event
    const done = createEnvelope('relay.human.slack.D123', { type: 'done', data: {} });
    await deliver('relay.human.slack.D123', done, client, streamState, callbacks);

    // Final update should preserve paragraph breaks (no collapse in handleDone)
    const updateCall = mockChatUpdate.mock.calls[0]?.[0] as { text: string };
    expect(updateCall.text).toBe('Para 1\n\nPara 2');
  });
});
```

Note: Since the test mocks `formatForPlatform` as a passthrough, the newline collapsing regex `formatted.replace(/\n{2,}/g, '\n')` is the key behavior being tested. In production, `slackify-markdown` inserts the `\n\n` separators that this regex collapses.

## Acceptance Criteria

- Intermediate `chat.update` calls use text with consecutive newlines collapsed to single newlines
- The final `handleDone` `chat.update` preserves full paragraph formatting (no newline collapsing)
- Streaming text appears as continuous flow during intermediate updates, not separated into paragraphs
- Existing streaming tests continue to pass

Telegram's `sendChatAction('typing')` indicator expires after 5 seconds. Currently `handleTypingSignal` calls it once and returns. This task adds interval-based refresh every 4 seconds, with proper cleanup on state change and adapter stop.

## Implementation

**File:** `packages/relay/src/adapters/telegram/outbound.ts`

Add a typing interval map and refresh constant near the top of the file, after the existing constants:

```typescript
/** Active typing intervals keyed by chatId. */
const typingIntervals = new Map<number, ReturnType<typeof setInterval>>();

/** Refresh interval for Telegram typing indicator (expires after 5s). */
const TYPING_REFRESH_MS = 4_000;
```

Replace the existing `handleTypingSignal` function (lines 161-176) with the interval-based version:

```typescript
/**
 * Handle a typing signal from the Relay and forward it to Telegram.
 *
 * Sends an immediate `typing` chat action and sets up an interval to
 * refresh it every 4 seconds (Telegram's indicator expires after 5s).
 * Clears the interval when the signal state changes to non-active.
 *
 * @param bot - The grammy Bot instance, or null if not started
 * @param subject - The Relay subject the typing signal was emitted on
 * @param state - The signal state ('active' | 'stopped' or other values)
 */
export async function handleTypingSignal(
  bot: Bot | null,
  subject: string,
  state: string,
): Promise<void> {
  if (!bot) return;

  const chatId = extractChatId(subject);
  if (chatId === null) return;

  if (state === 'active') {
    // Clear any existing interval (idempotent)
    clearTypingInterval(chatId);
    // Send immediately
    try {
      await bot.api.sendChatAction(chatId, TELEGRAM_TYPING_ACTION);
    } catch {
      // Typing signals are best-effort
    }
    // Refresh every 4 seconds
    const intervalId = setInterval(async () => {
      try {
        await bot.api.sendChatAction(chatId, TELEGRAM_TYPING_ACTION);
      } catch {
        clearTypingInterval(chatId);
      }
    }, TYPING_REFRESH_MS);
    typingIntervals.set(chatId, intervalId);
  } else {
    clearTypingInterval(chatId);
  }
}
```

Add the helper functions:

```typescript
/**
 * Clear the typing refresh interval for a specific chat.
 *
 * @param chatId - The Telegram chat ID to clear the interval for
 */
function clearTypingInterval(chatId: number): void {
  const existing = typingIntervals.get(chatId);
  if (existing !== undefined) {
    clearInterval(existing);
    typingIntervals.delete(chatId);
  }
}

/**
 * Clear all active typing intervals.
 *
 * Call on adapter stop to prevent leaked intervals.
 */
export function clearAllTypingIntervals(): void {
  for (const interval of typingIntervals.values()) clearInterval(interval);
  typingIntervals.clear();
}
```

**File:** `packages/relay/src/adapters/telegram/telegram-adapter.ts`

Import `clearAllTypingIntervals` and call it in `_stop()`:

```typescript
import { deliverMessage, handleTypingSignal, clearAllTypingIntervals } from './outbound.js';
```

In the `_stop()` method, add `clearAllTypingIntervals()` before the bot cleanup:

```typescript
protected async _stop(): Promise<void> {
  if (this.reconnectTimer) { clearTimeout(this.reconnectTimer); this.reconnectTimer = null; }
  if (this.signalUnsub) { this.signalUnsub(); this.signalUnsub = null; }
  clearAllTypingIntervals();

  if (this.bot) {
    // ... rest of existing cleanup
  }
}
```

## Tests

**File:** `packages/relay/src/adapters/telegram/__tests__/outbound.test.ts` (new file)

Create a dedicated outbound test file for the typing interval tests. This follows the pattern of having separate test files for inbound and outbound modules (like the Slack adapter does).

```typescript
import { describe, it, expect, vi, beforeEach, afterEach } from 'vitest';
import { handleTypingSignal, clearAllTypingIntervals } from '../outbound.js';
import type { Bot } from 'grammy';

// Mock inbound.js for extractChatId and constants
vi.mock('../inbound.js', () => ({
  SUBJECT_PREFIX: 'relay.human.telegram',
  MAX_MESSAGE_LENGTH: 4096,
  extractChatId: (subject: string) => {
    const parts = subject.split('.');
    const chatIdStr = parts[parts.length - 1];
    if (!chatIdStr) return null;
    const num = Number(chatIdStr);
    return Number.isNaN(num) ? null : num;
  },
}));

const mockSendChatAction = vi.fn().mockResolvedValue(true);

function buildMockBot(): Bot {
  return {
    api: {
      sendChatAction: mockSendChatAction,
    },
  } as unknown as Bot;
}

describe('typing indicator -- interval refresh', () => {
  let bot: Bot;

  beforeEach(() => {
    vi.clearAllMocks();
    vi.useFakeTimers();
    bot = buildMockBot();
  });

  afterEach(() => {
    clearAllTypingIntervals();
    vi.useRealTimers();
  });

  it('calls sendChatAction immediately on active signal', async () => {
    await handleTypingSignal(bot, 'relay.human.telegram.12345', 'active');
    expect(mockSendChatAction).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
    expect(mockSendChatAction).toHaveBeenCalledWith(12345, 'typing');
  });

  it('refreshes sendChatAction every 4 seconds', async () => {
    await handleTypingSignal(bot, 'relay.human.telegram.12345', 'active');
    expect(mockSendChatAction).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);

    // Advance 4 seconds -- first interval tick
    await vi.advanceTimersByTimeAsync(4_000);
    expect(mockSendChatAction).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(2);

    // Advance another 4 seconds -- second interval tick
    await vi.advanceTimersByTimeAsync(4_000);
    expect(mockSendChatAction).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(3);
  });

  it('clears interval on non-active signal', async () => {
    await handleTypingSignal(bot, 'relay.human.telegram.12345', 'active');
    expect(mockSendChatAction).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);

    // Stop typing
    await handleTypingSignal(bot, 'relay.human.telegram.12345', 'stopped');

    // Advance time -- should NOT trigger additional calls
    await vi.advanceTimersByTimeAsync(8_000);
    expect(mockSendChatAction).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
  });

  it('clears interval when sendChatAction fails', async () => {
    await handleTypingSignal(bot, 'relay.human.telegram.12345', 'active');

    // Make the interval tick fail
    mockSendChatAction.mockRejectedValueOnce(new Error('chat not found'));
    await vi.advanceTimersByTimeAsync(4_000);

    // Should not call again after failure
    await vi.advanceTimersByTimeAsync(4_000);
    // 3 total: 1 immediate + 1 failed interval + 0 after clear
    expect(mockSendChatAction).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(2);
  });

  it('replaces existing interval on repeated active signals', async () => {
    await handleTypingSignal(bot, 'relay.human.telegram.12345', 'active');
    await handleTypingSignal(bot, 'relay.human.telegram.12345', 'active');

    // Should have called immediately twice (once per active signal)
    expect(mockSendChatAction).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(2);

    // Only one interval should be running
    await vi.advanceTimersByTimeAsync(4_000);
    expect(mockSendChatAction).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(3);
  });

  it('does nothing when bot is null', async () => {
    await handleTypingSignal(null, 'relay.human.telegram.12345', 'active');
    expect(mockSendChatAction).not.toHaveBeenCalled();
  });

  it('clearAllTypingIntervals clears all active intervals', async () => {
    await handleTypingSignal(bot, 'relay.human.telegram.111', 'active');
    await handleTypingSignal(bot, 'relay.human.telegram.222', 'active');

    clearAllTypingIntervals();

    await vi.advanceTimersByTimeAsync(8_000);
    // Only the 2 immediate calls, no interval refreshes
    expect(mockSendChatAction).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(2);
  });
